# Auth Module Spec

## Scope

Standalone authentication module contracts for credentials, sessions, MFA, backup
codes, auth-owned storage, and the boundary between auth data and public users.

## Load when

Changing `internal/auth`, auth handlers, sessions, JWT/refresh behavior, MFA/TOTP,
backup codes, auth migrations, password policy, or user/auth model boundaries.

## Owns

- Auth logic: `backend/internal/auth/`
- Auth HTTP mount: `backend/internal/authhandler/`
- Session logic: `backend/internal/session/`
- JWT helpers: `backend/internal/jwt/`
- Models: `backend/models/auth.go`, public profile boundary in `backend/models/user.go`
- Tables: `auth_credentials`, `auth_totp_secrets`, `auth_backup_codes`, `user_sessions`
- Migration history: `backend/internal/migrations/009_auth_user_separation.sql`

## Contracts

- `users` stores public profile/account state, not password hashes, TOTP secrets,
  or backup code hashes.
- `auth_credentials` owns `password_hash` by `user_id`.
- `auth_totp_secrets` owns TOTP secret material and enabled state by `user_id`.
- `auth_backup_codes` owns one-use backup code hashes.
- `user_sessions` owns refresh-token/session state.
- Auth responses that need MFA state use `models.AuthUser`, which embeds the
  public user profile and adds response-only auth metadata such as `totp_enabled`.
- The core `models.User` must remain profile-only and must not cache or expose
  auth secrets.
- Username/email identity remains on the user profile side; auth tables link by
  `user_id`.

## Security Invariants

- Passwords are bcrypt hashed and never returned from repositories/services.
- Backup codes are stored hashed and become unusable after consumption.
- TOTP secrets are read only through auth service flows.
- Refresh/session tokens are stateful and revocable through `user_sessions`.
- Auth middleware must never depend on frontend permission checks.
- Sensitive auth failures should not leak which secret or factor was valid beyond
  the intended challenge flow.

## Migration Contract

- Fresh schema defines auth-owned tables directly in `001_schema.sql`.
- `009_auth_user_separation.sql` remains an idempotent legacy bridge: it copies
  legacy `users.password_hash`, `users.totp_secret`, and `users.totp_enabled`
  only if those columns exist, upserts by `user_id`, then drops legacy sensitive
  columns.
- Skaia has no legacy `users` backup-code column; backup codes are generated into
  `auth_backup_codes` after TOTP enablement.

## Testing Contract

- Auth service tests cover registration credential creation, login, TOTP secret
  enablement, backup code generation/use-once behavior, and TOTP disable cleanup.
- Auth/session changes require focused backend tests, and shared auth middleware
  changes should run the full backend suite.

## Invariants

- Keep auth module standalone; user service may depend on auth contracts, but auth
  secrets must not migrate back into user/profile/cache code.
- Do not expose card/payment-like secrets or auth secrets through generic user
  JSON, events, logs, WebSocket payloads, or cache values.
- Role/permission authorization is adjacent but distinct from credential/MFA
  authentication.

## Verify

- `rg "password_hash|totp_secret|totp_enabled|auth_backup_codes|user_sessions" backend/models backend/internal backend/internal/migrations -n`
- `backend/internal/auth/*_test.go`
- Full backend check when shared auth behavior changes:
  `env GOCACHE=/tmp/skaia-go-cache GOTMPDIR=/tmp JWT_SECRET=test-secret go test ./...`

